            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kyle Peterson\u2019s San Francisco life began as an escape from the predictable plains of suburban Ohio. Raised in a quiet, working-class family, he was known as a sensitive kid who always listened more than he spoke. He felt a pull to help people, a vague but persistent calling that led him to enroll in Social Work at SF State in the early 90s, drawn by the city\u2019s promise of acceptance and progressivism.\n\nHowever, the city\u2019s vibrant, chaotic underbelly pulled him in deeper than his studies. A decade blurred by addiction and instability followed, leaving his college plans shattered. He worked odd jobs\u2014barback, courier, bookstore clerk\u2014always on the periphery of the stability he once craved. His turning point wasn't a single event but a slow, painful crawl from rock bottom. Sobriety, found in a church basement meeting room in the Mission, became the foundation of a new life.\n\nNow, at 52, Kyle channels that hard-won experience into his role as a Peer Support Specialist. He understands the people he works with\u2014the recently housed, the students struggling with mental health, the clients battling substance use\u2014with an empathy that can\u2019t be taught. His own past is his greatest tool.\n\nHis daily routine is a testament to his grounded existence. He wakes early in his small, rent-controlled Inner Richmond apartment, the same one he\u2019s had for twenty years. His 3.5-mile bike commute to a SoMa non-profit is a daily meditation, a chance to watch the city wake up. His income is modest, but his life is rich with connection. His social circle is a tight-knit mix of colleagues and his \u201cfound family\u201d from his recovery fellowship.\n\nKyle has a complicated love for San Francisco; he\u2019s seen its beauty and its devastation firsthand. He has no ambitions for wealth or fame. His dream is to remain a steady, reliable presence for those still finding their way. He hopes to continue his work, maybe one day finish that degree for his own satisfaction, and simply enjoy the quiet peace of a life he fought so hard to reclaim."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was nineteen, on a Muni bus heading west for the first time in 1993. As it crested a hill, the Pacific Ocean suddenly filled the window, a vast, shimmering blue he\u2019d only ever seen in pictures. The sheer scale of it stole his breath. In that moment, the predictable grid of Ohio felt a million miles away. It wasn't just an ocean; it was a physical manifestation of possibility, a silent promise that his life, too, could be that expansive. It was the purest hope he would ever feel.\n\n***\n\n2.\nSometime in the late 90s, he was working as a bike courier, soaked through by a relentless winter rain. He delivered a package to a stunning Victorian in Noe Valley. Through the glowing window, he saw a family sharing a meal, their lives warm and contained. He was just a ghost on their porch, dripping and invisible. The shame felt colder than the rain, a profound sense of being utterly outside the world of warmth and connection he had once dreamed of joining. It was the quiet bottom.\n\n***\n\n3.\nIt was 2002, in a church basement in the Mission, the air thick with stale coffee and honest desperation. An older woman with trembling hands shared a story so similar to his own, he felt the words in his bones. He hadn't spoken a word in weeks of meetings, but he met her eyes across the room and gave a small, barely perceptible nod. She nodded back. In that silent, shared acknowledgment, the crushing weight of his isolation cracked. He wasn\u2019t alone. That tiny connection was the first brick in his new foundation.\n\n***\n\n4.\nJust last year, a young client at the SoMa non-profit\u2014a student from SF State, ironically\u2014confessed he felt lost and overwhelmed by the city\u2019s intensity. Kyle saw the ghost of his younger self in the kid's terrified eyes. He shared a small piece of his own story, of getting lost to find a different path. Seeing the flicker of recognition and relief on the student\u2019s face, Kyle understood his past wasn\u2019t a source of shame. It was his greatest tool, the very thing that allowed him to truly help.\n\n***\n\n5.\nLast Tuesday morning. Biking through Golden Gate Park on his way to work, the fog was so thick it dampened all sound, creating a private, moving silence. He wasn\u2019t racing to or from anything; he was just a part of the city\u2019s gentle rhythm. He felt the steady cadence of his pedaling and the cool, clean air on his face. A simple, profound gratitude washed over him. This feeling\u2014this quiet, earned peace\u2014was the success he had fought so hard to achieve."
